misconceptions.inferred_category_name: No misconception detected (correct array rotation logic)
misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes saving the last element, shifting all other elements right by one index from back to front, then placing the saved last element at index 0 will correctly perform a right shift with wrap-around.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: There is no conceptual gap here. This matches Java’s array semantics: assignments overwrite elements, so saving the last element first prevents it from being lost during the shift. Iterating from the end toward the front avoids overwriting values that are still needed.
misconceptions.error_manifestation: None. The program produces the expected shifted array for valid inputs, including edge case n = 0 (prints just 'Shifted: ' with no elements).
